    "summary": "The Aksumite Proto-Kingdom (c. 400–100 BC) was the early phase of the polity that would develop into the Aksumite Empire, one of the ancient world's major powers, centered in the highlands of modern Ethiopia and Eritrea — developing through contacts with South Arabian traders and settlers who brought writing, architecture, and commercial networks to the Horn of Africa.\n\nThe region of modern Tigray, Ethiopia, and Eritrea was influenced during this period by the Sabaean kingdom of South Arabia, whose colonists or traders established settlements and introduced the South Arabian script, monumental stone architecture, and religious practices. The indigenous D'mt kingdom (c. 800–400 BC) represents the pre-Aksumite phase of this development. The proto-Aksumite period saw the emergence of distinctly Ethiopian cultural forms from this Afro-Arabian synthesis. By around 100 BC, the settlement at Aksum was developing as a regional center. The fully developed Aksumite kingdom (from approximately 100 AD) would become one of the four great powers of the ancient world alongside Rome, Persia, and China — controlling the crucial Red Sea trade routes that connected the Mediterranean with [[event:1110|Indian Ocean Trade Routes]].",
